where $d=x_m -x_f$ with $x_m$ and $x_f$ the ages for male and female, respectively. \\
{{In our model for $\alpha$}}, in addition to this specification, the {{gender}} of the elder partner, represented by the sign of $d$, is also taken into account. This latter is captured through the second term of the denominator $\beta_1 d$ in equations \eqref{eq:paramFrankClayton} and \eqref{eq:paramGumbel}. Thus, {{for our model}} the copula association parameter for the Frank and the Clayton is expressed by
			\begin{eqnarray} \label{eq:paramFrankClayton}
					\alpha(d) =  \frac{\beta_0}{1 + \beta_1 d + \beta_2 {\lvert {d} \rvert} }, \quad \beta_0,\beta_1, \beta_2 \in {\mathbb{R}}.
			\end{eqnarray}	
		Since the copula parameter $\alpha$ in the Gumbel and  Joe copulas is restricted to be greater than $1$, the corresponding dependence parameter in \eqref{eq:paramGumbel} is allowed to have an intercept of $1$ and we write
			\begin{eqnarray} \label{eq:paramGumbel}
					\alpha(d) = 1+  \frac{\beta_0}{1 + \beta_1 d + \beta_2 {\lvert {d} \rvert} }, \quad \beta_0,\beta_1, \beta_2 \in {\mathbb{R}}.
			\end{eqnarray}
It can be seen that if $\beta_1 < 0$, the dependence parameter is lower when husband is younger than wife, i.e. $d<0$. Also when $d$ tends to infinity, the dependence parameter goes to $0$ for Frank and Clayton and $1$ for the Gumbel copula, thus tending towards the independence assumption. {{Note in passing that instead of taking}} $d^2$ as in equation \eqref{eq:paramYoun}, we use $ {\lvert {d} \rvert}$ in both \eqref{eq:paramFrankClayton} and \eqref{eq:paramGumbel} for the representation of the absolute age difference. 







\subsection{{{Estimation of Parameters }}}	
The maximum likelihood procedure has been widely used to fit lifetime data to copula models, see e.g., {{  \cite{lawless2011statistical, shih1995inferences,carriere2000bivariate}}}. A priori, this method consists in estimating jointly the marginal and copula parameters at once. However, given the {{huge}} number of parameters to be estimated at the same time, {{this approach is}} computationally intensive.  {{Therefore}},  we adopt a procedure that allows the determination of marginal and copula parameters, separately. In this respect, Joe and Xu \cite{joe1996estimation} have proposed a two step technique which, firstly estimates the marginal parameters $\theta_j, j = m,f,$  and the copula parameter $\alpha(d)$ in the  second step.
